          <section class="faq-section mt-5">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-list">
              <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>How do you convert a decimal to a fraction?</h3>
                <p>To convert a decimal to a fraction, write the decimal over 1, then multiply both top and bottom by 10 for every number after the decimal point. Finally, simplify the fraction by finding the greatest common divisor.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>What is 0.5 as a fraction?</h3>
                <p>0.5 as a fraction is 1/2. You calculate this by writing 0.5/1, multiplying by 10/10 to get 5/10, and dividing by 5 to get 1/2.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>How do I convert a repeating decimal to a fraction?</h3>
                <p>To convert a repeating decimal to a fraction, set the decimal to x, multiply x by a power of 10 equal to the number of repeating digits, subtract the original equation, and solve for x.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>What is 0.75 as a fraction?</h3>
                <p>0.75 as a fraction is 3/4. You get this by writing 75/100 and simplifying by dividing both the numerator and denominator by 25.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Why do we need to simplify fractions?</h3>
                <p>Simplifying fractions makes them easier to read, understand, and use in further mathematical calculations by reducing the numbers to their smallest possible whole numbers.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
